{
  "family": "Ferrier Reaction/Rearrangement",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CC(=O)O[C@H]1C=C[C@H](OC(C)=O)[C@H](OC(C)=O)O1"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "CC(=O)O[C@H]1C=C[C@H](OC(C)=O)[C@@H](O)O1"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a canonical example of the Ferrier rearrangement (Type I), specifically the conversion of a glycal (tri-O-acetyl-D-glucal) to a 2,3-unsaturated glycoside. The reaction involves the allylic rearrangement of the double bond within the dihydropyran ring and nucleophilic attack at the anomeric carbon. Water acts as the nucleophile, leading to a pseudoglycal product. This example clearly illustrates the core transformation of the Ferrier reaction: cleavage of the C1-O bond and formation of a new C1-Nu bond with a shift of the double bond from C1=C2 to C2=C3.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The substrate is a protected glycal, a specific carbohydrate derivative essential for this reaction. The transformation is a unique allylic rearrangement within a heterocyclic system, distinct from general glycosylation reactions, Claisen rearrangements, or simple alkene additions. The use of a simple nucleophile (water) and standard protecting groups (acetates) avoids introducing complex motifs that could collide with other named reactions."
  }
}
